  "diary": "Monday started crisp and clear—perfect bike weather. I almost felt guilty staying in the U-District all day while the sun kept getting better. The Light Rail closure didn't touch my commute, thankfully, though I heard people grumbling about it at Solstice when I grabbed lunch. Everyone was talking about the USA-Wales match at 11, but I was already deep in wireframes by then. Kept my head down, which felt good. The afternoon blurred into design critiques and Slack threads. By the time I got home, my legs were tired from the bike ride but my mind felt settled. Made something simple for dinner, then settled into my knitting with a podcast—the kind of evening that feels like a small victory. Just quiet, purposeful, mine.",
  "thought_process": "I knew the World Cup match would draw crowds downtown, and honestly, I wasn't tempted. I'm in a focused work phase on a redesign that matters, and skipping the bar scene felt like the right call for my headspace. The weather was almost distracting—I kept glancing out the office windows—but I leaned into that restless energy by biking home instead of taking the bus. It grounded me somehow. The Light Rail closure barely registered because my routine didn't depend on it, which made me feel oddly fortunate. By evening, I was ready for something tactile and slow. Knitting always resets me.",
